2":"about 1152","1218":"1218","Kleve, Kleef, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Heiliges Römisches Reich":"Cleves, Kleve, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany","Dinslaken, Düsseldorf, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Deutschland":"Dinslaken, Wesel, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Wangen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Arlis, Erik, Nels, Obert.","Norwegian: variant of   Vangen  .","German and possibly also Flemish: variant of German and Dutch   Wang  . This surname is most common in Belgium, especially in its German-speaking part in Wallonia."],"variants":[{"name":"Vangen","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads named with the definite singular of <i>vang</i>, from Old Norse <i>vangr</i> ‘field’, ‘meadow’. Compare   Wangen  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Von Wangen was born about 1152, her father, Albero I von Wangen und Burgeis, was 17 and her mother, Mathilde von Eschenbach, was 8. She had at least 2 daughters with Antonius Van Dinslaken. She died about 1226, at the age of 76."},"et":{"about 1152–about 1226":"umbes 1152–umbes 1226","1152–1226":"1152–1226","1160–1194":"1160–1194","1162–1226":"1162–1226","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1170–1218":"1170–1218","–Male":"Surnud","1195–1224":"1195–1224","1137–1194":"1137–1194","1146–1249":"1146–1249","1165":"1165","1152":"1152","1195":"1195","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","26 June 1194":"26. juuni 1194","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1249":"1249","1226":"1226","1137":"1137","1224":"1224","circa 1195":"umbes 1195","1146":"1146","about 1226":"umbes 1226","about 1152":"umbes 1152","1218":"1218","Kleve, Kleef, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Heiliges Römisches Reich":"Kleve, Kleve, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Saksamaa","Dinslaken, Düsseldorf, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Deutschland":"Dinslaken, Kreis Wesel, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"about 1152–about 1226":"noin 1152–noin 1226","1152–1226":"1152–1226","1160–1194":"1160–1194","1162–1226":"1162–1226","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","1170–1218":"1170–1218","–Male":"Kuollut","1195–1224":"1195–1224","1137–1194":"1137–1194","1146–1249":"1146–1249","1165":"1165","1152":"1152","1195":"1195","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","26 June 1194":"26. kesäkuuta 1194","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1249":"1249","1226":"1226","1137":"1137","1224":"1224","circa 1195":"noin 1195","1146":"1146","about 1226":"noin 1226","about 1152":"noin 1152","1218":"1218","Kleve, Kleef, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Heiliges Römisches Reich":"Kleve, Kleve, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Saksa","Dinslaken, Düsseldorf, 